XPO Logistics terminal LSL experienced a UN1992 19122 Lacquer Thinner Fast release from (6) 5-gallon metal pails. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-gallons of product released to an 8’ x 10’ area of the trailer floor. The lids of the pails seemed to be leaking as a possible result of being stacked and crushed. The damaged pails were collected into an 85-gallon poly drum. Absorbents were then deployed and worked into the impacted area. The impacted absorbents, pads, pallet pieces, and PPE were collected into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: The shipper shipped a box containing three laptops and six tablets, all of which still had their Li-Ion batteries installed, without placing either a Class 9 diamond label or UN3481 Li-Ion battery sticker on the outside of the box.  One of the cells in the Li-Ion battery of one of the laptops started generating a current, despite the laptop being powered off.  This resulted in a buildup of heat sufficient to melt the malfunctioning battery cell, part of the laptop case, and some of the bubble wrap surrounding the laptop.  It also gave off smoke and an unpleasant odor.

column169: Hazmat was found at door 125 in the load end ready to go to the next load point. The outbound sort manager walked passed it and noticed a very strong odor coming from the box. QA was contacted immediately to inspect the box. I noticed a little wet spot on one of the bottom corners of the package and brought it over to the office in a lined tote for further inspection. The inner drum seamed to have a poor quality closure that caused some of the contents to spill out and make it a little noticeable to the naked eye. Once the package was fully opened, the corrugated liner seamed to be wet also to confirm that the hazmat was damaged and could have possibly been damaged while it was on the vehicle when the driver returned from the pick up but could have dried do to the Acetone & Isopropyl Alcohol ingredient that makes up the product.

R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site. FCE personnel overpacked the damaged bags in one (1) 95-gallon drum. Crews utilized hand tools and absorbents to remediate teh site and collected all impacted material in one (1) 55-gallon drum.

column169: On Thursday, July 4th, 2024, at 1057 hours, CSX personnel operating the L81004 observed GATX 5618, a loaded tank car of Sulfuric Acid, in the train, was leaking from the protective housing. The car was held by the CSX train crew on the Main Line at MP SGC 621 outside of Rockmart GA for further investigation.   The shipper, GEO Specialty Chemicals Inc, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report 2024-07-04-00063). Marion Environmental, Inc. (MEI), a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the liquid line closure cap less than tool tight.   Contractor personnel tightened the liquid line cap to secure the car.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative (Dan Parker, GEO Logistics Manager, 404-782-1699).  The car was released for transportation.

column170: Do not rely on product manufacturer to ensure product is properly prepared for reshipping. Inform manufacturer if their packaging is not adequate to protect contents. Inspect all containers for defects and leaks, check all seals, and securely tighten all caps before packing.  Use slotted corrugated dividers, doublewall cartons, and extra padding and/or overpack as needed to protect fragile containers.

column18: PACIFIC SCIENTIFIC ENERGETIC MATERIALS COMPANY (CALIFORNIA) LLC
column169: On July 1, 2024, we received a package from Meggitt Safety Systems. The package that we received contained a Non-classified explosive material, that should have been shipped on a DOT-SP 8451 special permit pipe. The material arrived to our facility in a standard Uline 12x12x12 fiberboard box. These boxes are not UN popped for Hazardous materials. Inside that box was a FedEx "Small Box", that contained paperwork and 7 live explosive parts.   Once opened the package was separated into different holding area for examination. As this was a return shipment to out facility, thankfully the parts were sealed in the factory ESD bags with labels.   There were no hazardous material labels affixed to the outside of the container. No DG forms were completed.   Because of the untested nature of the parts, they were required to be shipped in a DOT-SP 8451 special permit   pipe. That pipe, per the permit should be, either a 4" or 6" schedule 80 seamless pipe, with closures at both ends, rated for containment of 25 g PETN. Also, the specific label should have read, Articles, explosive, n.o.s (*), 1.4E.
column170: We immediately notified the Shipping Manager for Meggitt Safety Systems of the shipment. We also stressed the importance of properly shipping this material, and the DOT fines that can be levied for failure to comply.

column43: ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID, N.O.S., AT OR ABOVE 100 C AND BELOW ITS FLASH POINT (INCLUDING MOLTEN METALS, MOLTEN SALTS, ETC.)
column169: On 07/10/2024, at 0541hrs., personnel in the CSXT Russell Yard discovered SIRX23534, a loaded tank car of Elevated Temperature, Liquid N.O.S. (Asphalt), leaking from under the jacket at the B-end brake support bracket onto the break assembly. The car was isolated and the shipper, Marathon Petroleum, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2024-0710-0049). Quick Response, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found product had leaked from under the jacket onto the brake assembly support but turned viscous as it cooled down and was malleable but solid. Subsequent investigation determined that the product released from the car due to a crack in the tank shell.  The car was held out of transportation pending further investigation and observation by the owner and FRA, and pending a procedure to safely unload the car.

column169: After loading hazardous waste at the shipper's location, the Veolia operator closed the pneumatic internal valve of the tanker and proceeded to disconnect the PTO hydraulic lines when it was noticed that a puddle was forming at the back of the tanker. The Veolia operator proceeded to close the manual valve to stop the release. The generators spill response team was notified.    Mechanical evaluation of the tanker revealed that debris had caused the valve stem to seize and prevent the valve from fully closing. The Veolia operator also reported that he was distracted at the end of the loading process and failed to close the secondary manual valve or place a cap on the hose.
column170: The tanker valve is being repaired. Additionally, a safety alert has been sent to the group detailing the importance of avoiding distractions during critical steps of hazardous materials handling.

column169: The package was found in unload coming off the trailer. The package was leaking from the bottom when QA found it. QA placed the package in the red bin and brought it to the hazmat cage. The bottles of multi surface cleaner inside the package had no inner packing to protect the bottles from being damaged. The bottles had no caps and one of the bottles were punctured from the bottom. The corrosive label was on the side of the box.

The package was found wet on the outside of the box. Proper PPE was used to inspect the package. Upon inspection it was discovered that one of the bottles had a loose cap which led to the leak. The package was then placed in a hazmat bin. There was no inner packaging inside the box which likely helped contribute to the spill.

On 07/12/2024 this shipment containing hidden dangerous goods was discovered during the shipment inspection process at the at the DHL PNS Service Center, 5601 Joe Elliot Way Pensacola, FL 32503 Transportation by road has been confirmed.

column169: On July 11th, 2024 I drove a load from Marathon Refinery in Carson, CA to Foreman, AR. When I reached Lake Havasa, AZ it was a temperature of 125 degrees F. I reached the truck stop Pilots in Lake Havasa to take a 30 minute break and did a trailer inspection on the trailer 1145. I noticed the trailer was leaking the product out of the top of the tank. I rushed to grab some trash cans that the truck stop had next to my trailer to catch any liquid that was draining down the side of the tank. I climbed up the ladder to inspect where the leak was coming from and noticed it was leaking from the ARV Valve and also had 40 PSI of pressure and nowhere to relieve the pressure from. I cleaned up the tank and kept an eye on it and waited for temps to cool down. Once the temps cooled down I was able to relieve the pressure from the domes by cracking one of the ears. All the pressure was relieved and the leak stopped and was contained until the HAZMAT team showed up at 0900 in the morning to clean up.

column43: DYES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S. OR DYE INTERMEDIATES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S.
column169: Bulk Truck#205997 was put on door. There was a foul odor coming from the vehicle which smelled like vinegar. The bulk truck was pulled off the door and parked in the yard with the back door left open in order to air it out. Later during the sort, the bulk truck was put back on door however the odor did not dissipate. Once some packages were pulled out, the spill was evident. Blue dye was all over the floor on the right side of the vehicle. A(formerly) white pail was on its side with the top cap open. The pail was covered in blue dye which covered the label and any other information. We started pulling out the leaked-on packages and came across a second white pail which was identical to the first and listed as 1 of 2. Upon inspection, a Corrosive Class 8 diamond label was discovered on the side of the pail. There were SDS sheets attached to the pail. Also on the pail was a manufacturing label which listed UN#, DOT shipping name of material, Technical name, Hazardous Class and Packing Group. No Hazardous Materials Certification Form was submitted, no OP-900LL on the pail and there was no"HAZ" marking on the FXG shipping label. The shipper shipped this as an Undeclared Hazmat(TRACKING#777176962630). This shipment was classified as a PGI. Since we were dealing with a high danger hazmat and all 6 gallons had spilled out, it was determined that any intemal attempt at cleanup was beyond our capabilities and this incident needed to be reported. My first call was to the Emergency Spill number listed on the container which is required of the shipper. The company listed was CHEMTREC 1-800-424-9300. I filed a spill incident report with them and received a report number(#224070300268). They then instructed me to contact our company's Emergency Spill Response Service. The spill met the criteria listed for our FXG Emergency Spill Response Service 1-833-394-7745. Once contacted, I provided them with all the information that they required, and they assigned Alert#212661 to our request for assistance. They dispatched a cleanup team and instructed me to meet them when they arrived as well as remain on site during the cleanup process.

column169: On July 8, 2024, at 1745 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in Jefferson, Georgia regarding the release of Caustic Soda Prills. Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of Caustic Soda Prills (UN1823, 8, II). The release was caused by a rollover accident that impacted a 360ft x 50ft area of soil and an adjacent concrete lined drainage ditch that contained 635 gallons of free-standing impacted rainwater. Contractors collected the damaged cargo that was still in the trailer, neutralized and collected all free-standing liquid with a vac truck, excavated all impacted soil, then placed seed and straw. Contractors took 635 gallons of impacted rainwater in a vac truck and 11 roll-offs of impacted soil and damaged cargo offsite for proper disposal.

column169: FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED WET IN APPEARANCE BY THE SWEEPER IN SECTION-C AT DOOR 27. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN 2 MINUTES A DESIGNATED RESPONDER ARRIVED, DONNING PROPER PPE AND WITH A FULLY STOCKED SPILL CART. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON), THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THERE WAS MINISCULE PUNCTURE HOLE AT THE BASE CORNER ON A CLOSED HEAD, POLY, 5-GAL PAIL, CAUSING APPROX. 14 OUNCES OF THE LIQUID PRODUCT TO SPILL THROUGH THE BREACH AND INTO THE CARTON. THERE WAS NO INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL AND THE OUTER CONTAINER WAS A SINGLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 275 LBS PER SQ IN BURSTING TEST.

column169: On 7/10/2024 at 09:45 hours, DOT Inspector Alan Fisher was conducting an inspection at the CSX Manville Yard in Manville, NJ.  Mr. Fisher reported a suspect release from the top of NATX301283, a loaded tank car of Acetone.  CSX isolated the car and notified the shipper, Sabic Innovative Plastics, via CHEMTREC (Report #2024-0710-00165).  Marion Environmental Inc. (MEI), a CSX  emergency response contractor, responded to inspect the car.   MEI personnel verified a release of product vapor due to a blind flange on the pressure plate have no gasket installed.  Contractor personnel installed a gasket between blind flange and pressure plate; secured the nuts to stop the release.  The condition found and corrective measure were communicated to the shipper’s representative (Skyler Davis, 812-781-4454).  Following the emergency repairs outlined, the car was held pending bubble leak test by a certified mobile repair unit.

On Tuesday, July 2, 2024, a CN mechanical performing an inspection observed that the bottom outlet valve appeared to be leaking from tank car # UTLX 210420 along with a strong Ethanol type odor in the area. The employee notified the Waterloo Yard Master who in turn notified the CN Dangerous Goods Team. The tank car was set out to an isolation track (WA90) for inspection by a CN emergency response contractor. A CN emergency response contractor was dispatched to the location for mitigation. The contractor performed an inspection of the tank car and found the bottom outlet valve to be leaking from the threads of the bottom outlet valve cap. It was determined that there was a failure in the sealing surface of the valve seat to include a defective gasket. (The BOV cap was found to be less than tool tight and the BOV in the closed position and pinned upon initial inspection). CN emergency response contractor did observe cable seal to be correctly in place. The BOV cap was removed, and it was observed to be leaking past the closed ball. The BOV valve handle was cycled several times to the open and closed position to free any debris that may have been trapped in the BOV sealing surface potentially causing the leak. The BOV cap was then removed and observed for 20 minutes to ensure there was no further leakage from the valve. It was noted that the BOV cap gasket was deformed and was replaced. The bottom outlet valve cap was then re-installed and tightened with a 36" pipe wrench. Upon tightening the BOV cap, CN emergency response contractor proceeded to place new cable seals on the BOV / Cap.

column169: On July 20, 2024, at 1605 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in Albuquerque, New Mexico regarding the release of Ecolab Aqua Balance Pool and Spa Disinfectant. Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of 15 gallons of Ecolab Aqua Balance Pool and Spa Disinfectant (UN1791, 8, III) from (1)15-gallon plastic drum. The release was caused by a puncture from a pallet due to a load shift and contained to a 3ft x 25ft area of the trailer floor, and a 4ft x 2ft area of asphalt beneath the trailer. Contractors placed the damaged empty drum in an overpack then cleaned the release with absorbents and the proper PPE. The overpack was secured in the trailer to be forwarded on to the original consignee. All waste was containerized in (1) 55-gallon DF and staged onsite by contractors for proper disposal.

Hepaco contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all clean-up activities. Upon  arrival, contractors observed approximately 2 ounces released from (1) 275-gallon IBC plastic tote. The release was caused by a loose cap and impacted the top of the tote and cardboard. Contractors wiped down the impacted area and tightened the cap. The spent rags and impacted cardboard was placed into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum and staged onsite by contractors for proper disposal.      approximately (2) ounces of   CRW 9220 Corrosion Inhibitor (Flammable liquid, toxic, n.o.s., (Methanol, Isopropanol), UN1992, 3, 6.1, III) from (7) 55-gallon poly drums. Contractors were dispatched to clean up the release with absorbents and the proper PPE. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed that the release was contained to the tops of the drums only, contractors wiped down the totes and tightened the drum caps so the cargo could be forwarded on to the original consignee. All waste generated was containerized in (1) 55-gallon poly drum which was then taken offsite by contractors for proper disposal.  IF NO RELEASE Contractors were unable to locate any damaged cargo. No waste was generated from this event.

column169: The contents of this shipment began to spill after the lids popped open becoming slightly ajar. This likely could have been avoided through the inclusion of more inner packing and the inclusion of a LQ diamond on the outer packing as the package probably would have been handled as a LQ shipment.

When the Veolia employees arrived at Martha Jefferson hospital and opened the back of the truck, they discovered that the load had shifted during transportation. This caused a 12 gallon medical waste bin from Sentara to be crushed and the lid popped off. It is estimated that less than a pint of liquid spilled onto the floor and the surrounding containers. The spill was contained to the back of the truck. There were no injuries as a result of the spill. The spill was cleaned and the containers affected were overpacked without further incident.
column170: The incident was caused due to inadequate load securement The Veolia EHS manager discussed the importance of proper load securement with the employees involved with the shipment.

column169: At VCE, on 7/09/2024, Delta Dangerous Goods management was notified of a shipment of nine shipping containers containing oxygen bottles was discovered on the ramp. While all Dangerous Goods markings and labels were obliterated, and the oxygen bottles were shipped as empty under IATA DGR Exception 3.2.2.4.1 for empty cylinders of Division 2.2 gases, one of the bottles was still pressurized.  This event is under investigation.
column170: Immediate Corrective actions. The root cause analysis is on-going: - Reminder of good practices sent to all logistics locations with the packing service contact list in case of doubt - Working procedure on hazardous materials - Instruction sent not to sign a DELTA document without approval of an authorized DELTA representative - Investigate if Logaero's storekeepers an use their "@logaero.fr" email addresses during their service to Delta in order to withdraw any misunderstanding regarding their level of decision with Delta - DG IATA/ADR training refresh to be planned for the storekeepers

A Veolia employee was offloading pallets of drums from a trailer at Veolia's 1- day intransit facility in Menomonee Falls, WI. In the process of offloading the trailer, the forks on the forklift extended past the end of the pallet due to it being a smaller size pallet. The employee was unaware of their surroundings and length of forks, allowing the forks to puncture a drum loaded in the truck behind the pallet that was being offloaded. Approximately 1/2 of a gallon of material leaked before the employee was able to secure the drum from leaking any further. The duration of the spill was approximately 30 seconds. The material was then cleaned and the employees reported the spill of material. The drum that was damaged with the forklift was overpacked for safe transportation to the disposal facility.
column170: Veolia employees and supervisors at the Menomonee Falls facility have been advised to be aware of the material on and off of pallets, as well as awareness of the length of forks/equipment being used to offload material.

The area where the liquid came out was not apparent.  The cap was tight, and it didn't leak from there.  The spill was at the bottom of the shipping box, and you can see the ring from the bottom of the container.  But no apparent seam split or hole.  There was an indent in the container, but it was toward the top of the container.  But there was liquid in the plastic bag that the container was in with a zip tie.

column43: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH NOT LESS THAN 20 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 40 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column169: FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED WET IN APPEARANCE BY AN UNLOADER IN SECTION-C. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PACKAGE, HE EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN 1 MINUTE A DESIGNATED RESPONDER ARRIVED DONNING PROPER PPE AND WITH A FULLY STOCKED SPILL CART. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE, THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON), THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAP ON 1 OF 4 POLY, 1-GAL JUGS WAS LOOSE BY 1/4 ROTATION, CAUSING APPROXIMATELY 12 OUNCES OF THE LIQUID PRODUCT TO SPILL THROUGH THE BREACH AND INTO THE CARTON. THERE WAS NO INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL AND SECONDARY CONTAINMENT CONSISTED OF A DOUBLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 51 LBS/IN EDGE CRUSH TEST (ECT).

TWO AIR DANGEROUS GOODS PACKAGES SHIPPING WITH AN IATA DECLARATION, HAZMAT LABELS AND MARKS WERE FOUND LEAKING AT THE UPS WORLDPORT FACILITY IN LOUISVILLE, KENTUCKY. THE SHIPMENT HAD PASSED AN ACCEPTANCE AUDIT AT THE ORIGIN FACILITY, FLOWN RNO TO SDF PRIOR TO THE INCIDENT DISCOVERY IN LOUISVILLE, KENTUCKY. EACH PACKAGE CONTAINS TWO X 2.5 GALLON CONTAINERS OF VAPONA CONCENTRATE INSECTICIDE. THE ADDITIONAL TRACKING NUMBER ALSO LEAKING IN THE SHIPMENT IS 1Z0V044X0118441037. INITIAL REVIEW OF THE CONTENTS REVEALS EACH PACKAGE HAD ONE CONTAINER THAT LEAKED APPROXIMATELY ONE LITER FROM WHAT APPEARS TO BE A LOOSE CLOSURE. BOTH PACKAGES ARE ON HOLD PENDING POSSIBLE FAA INSPECTION.

The generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal in a secure location. The generated waste will remain onsite for Dayton Freight’s contracted hazardous waste vendor to coordinate disposal.

column169: Circle K notified ERTS of a fuel overfill at a Mapco in Nashville, TN (Circle K bought out Mapco). It was reported that approximately 100 gallons of premium unleaded gasoline released due to the cap coming loose on the veerder-root system (measures the depth of how much fuel in the tank) when they were filling it. He has his lead driver on the way with oil dri, spill pads, and absorbent snakes and the area has been coned off. The release impacted asphalt and has spilled into the roadway, shutting down the Firestone next door. No storm drains or waterways are impacted by the release that he is aware of. He is not aware of any road closures or emergency personnel on site at this time but believes management will be notifying the fire department.

column169: On 7/30/2024 at approximately 1330, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 154002 at the station location in Temecula, reporting a dangerous goods spill.  The shipment consisted of one plastic jug packaged in a FedEx padded pack.  The commidity was discovered leaking from the closure, resulting in spillage that compromised the outer labeling.  Based off the product name, Dangerous Goods Administration located an online safety data sheet, idnetifying the commodity as UN 3082 Environmentally hazardous substance, n.o.s.; however, the shipment was not properly packaged in strong rigid outer packaging, which voided the use of Special Provision A197.  The shipment is being held, pending an FAA investigation.

column169: the tanker was filled to capacity in order to get as much out of Amcor's tank as possible.  Tanker has a capacity of 5350 gallons. On the paperwork it shows 5346 gallons was loaded. The material in the tanker started to get hot and run out of the dome and onto the ground. 1 gallon of material leaked into secondary containment and was cleaned up in house. The cause of the spill was that the tanker was overfilled.
column170: The driver manager told the driver that when picking up material at that facility to only pick up 5000 gal so not to have this incident occur again. Drivers were also instructed about leaving headspace in containers.

column169: On July 8th 2024, at approximately 11:30am, Union Railroad Train 50a was in the process of entering the Port Perry and Dexter Yards with a 96 car loaded iron ore train.  The train was led my four locomotives.  Brakes were applied to the locomotives only and allowed to release on the remainder of the train.  This caused a great deal of force in the train that allowed the cars to leave the track.  Rail dislodged during the derailment impacted the fuel tank of the third from lead locomotive causing it to spill its contents of fuel.  Three of the four locomotives derailed as well as five of the 96 loaded ore cars.  No other material was spilled, the remaining locomotives had no leaks.    Internal responders were notified and responded to the derailment.  The spill response plan was followed alerting the required agencies.  A derailment contractor was called in to re-rail the train, and internal forces were assembled to repair the track.  The liquid product on the ground was collected as quickly as possible into buckets, however most of the product entered the ballast and surrounding soil.  The nearby river was monitored for signs of a sheen, inlets were checked but it was found the fuel had not reached either.  A spill contractor was dispatched to provide lined dumpsters for the contaminated soil.  The contractor also provided a vacuum truck to clean up the track area that could not be reached with an excavator.  Contaminated soil was placed in the lined dumpsters.  Dumpsters are staged for pickup when manifests are created and samples are analyzed.   The area of the spill will be restored with new ballast.  Any recovered fuel will be filtered and re-used elsewhere on the railroad.   The locomotive with the broken fuel tank was checked in the morning and recorded to have about 900 gallons of fuel before the trip.  40 gallons were recovered from the tank before re-railing the locomotive.  The maximum amount spilled would be approximately 860 gallons, however some of that amount was likely used in transit between the start of duty and the derailment.

On July 6, 2024, one (1) 330-gallon tote of UN3109 was damaged and released approximately five (5) gallons of product to the loading dock and tote. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Ancon Services (AS) to remediate the impacted site. FCE personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted area and worked them in with hand tools. Approximately 30-gallons of UN3267 were hand pumped into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. All impacted material were containerized into one (1) additional 55-gallon poly drum. The crew pumped the virgin product into one (1) new tote for continued shipment.

column169: July 8, 2024: On this date a driver for LPG Logistics USDOT 3142354 (C Three Logistics USDOT 2961868) was delivering the above listed material to a client in Berlin NJ. The Driver and receiver's operator failed to ensure the hose was empty of product prior to disconnecting the hose. The material within the hose ( Approx 5-20 gallons) spilled on the ground. The area was immediately secured. The product was contained with dry absorbent and absorbing pads and properly disposed of via an authorized recovery company. The report is being submitted at the request of the manufacturer/shipper. No injuries, deaths, fire, waterway involvement. NRC notified on 7-9-24 NRC # 1404204. NJDEP 24-07-09-1610-25 (Closed)

column169: Clean Harbors was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 3ft-by-5ft area of the trailer floor and estimated that thirty (30) gallons of material was released due to four (4) crushed 5-gallon plastic pails. The damaged plastic pails were placed into one (1) 30-gallon and one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. Clean Harbors personnel deployed a neutralizer to the impacted area and then used a granular absorbent to gather the spent material. The contractor placed the recovered spent absorbents into one (1) 30-gallon poly drum. One (1) 55-gallon poly drum was generated containing impacted pallet pieces. One (1) additional 15-gallon poly drum was generated for the contractor’s PPE. All waste generated from this response was staged onsite at the terminal in a secure location prior to the contractor demobilization. The generated waste will remain onsite for J.B. Hunt contracted hazardous waste vendor to coordinate disposal.

column169: The WLE Brewster Yard Car Inspector found tank car PROX 44241 leaking from the bottom outlet valve.  He called the Brewster Yardmaster who then called myself, John Vergis, Hazardous Materials Officer for the WLE.  I came out to look at the car and found that the bottom outlet valve of the car was indeed leaking through the valve cap.  The valve handle was in the closed position and would not close any more.  It was a disengaging ball valve.  I removed the seal from the valve handle #1880761 and the valve stem #1880762, so that I could try to cycle the valve to see if I could get the leak to stop.    I could not get the valve to move in either direction either with the valve handle or with a pipe wrench directly on the valve stem. I tried to tighten the valve cap with a 36" pipe wrench but I could not get it any more tight and the leak would not stop.  I put containment under the leaking valve and called Specialized Professional Services out of Washington , PA to come out to transload the car into another rail car.  They arrived about 2300 hrs. to transload and completed the transload about 0600 the next morning. On Monday, 7-8-2024, SPSI came back out to clean the interior of the car so that it could go back to the MarkWest plant in Jewett to be repaired.  After it was cleaned, I removed the bottom outlet cap and with a 36" pipe wrench, and a second person, we were able to get the valve to open.  I looked up into the valve and saw that the nylon seal on the ball was shredded which was the cause of the leak.

On 07/09/2024, at 1300 hrs., CSX Hazardous Materials Manager Scott Karcher discovered in the CSX Ensel Yard, the GATX29637, a loaded tank car of Acetone, releasing product vapor from the vacuum relief valve (VRV).  The car was isolated and the shipper, Altivia Chemical, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2024-07-09-00182). EnviroServe, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and determined the VRV was faulty.  Contractor personnel removed the defective vacuum relief valve and applied a securement plug to stop the vapor release.  The issue was identified, and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative (Jeremy Walker, 740-533-5232, jwalker@altivia.com).

column169: XPO Logistics terminal LAO experienced a UN1993 Unisol Liquid Red BK-50 release from a 330-gallon metal tote when delivering to the customer. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup and containment. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-gallons of product released to the tote body and an 8’ x 8’ area of the concrete lot. The tote fell off of the lift gate due to improper handling, resulting in the release. The tote was up righted and wiped down with a solvent and pads. The impacted concrete was cleaned with a solvent and pads to remove the material. Granular absorbents were also deployed and worked in. The impacted pads and absorbents were then collected into (2) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was transported back to XPO in Amarillo, TX for terminal personnel to manage.

On Tuesday, July 23, 2024, at 08:39 hours, a CSX Mechanical Manager reported an odor in the area of PROX 99823, a loaded tank car of Anhydrous Ammonia. The car was isolated and the shipper, PCS Sales, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report 2024-0723-00094). Marion Environmental, Inc. (MEI), a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and confirmed anon-accident release due to the B end liquid line valve partially open and secondary closure plug not properly installed. Contractor personnel closed the liquid line valve and resecured the valve’s closure plug. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative- Matt Painter (706-564-8118).  At the request of the FRA, the car was held pending OTMA.

column169: On July 23,2024, TAG inspected trailer MCKZ550219, booking SEA 1040763. This load sailed NB on the North Star voyage 24115 that departed Tacoma on 7/19/2024. Upon inspecting it, TAG found an undeclared hazardous item of 1 box of UN 1090 Acetone Class flammable liquid not marked as limited quantity. The trailer was placarded as limited quantity and should have been placarded as Class 3. This item not being manifested could cause the trailer to be stowed not according to the proper segregation requirements. The trailer sailed with undeclared hazardous material inside and was stowed on the Vessel.
column170: This finding resulted in a Hazardous Corrective Action to be completed by our customer/Shipper. There corrective action and details of the incident are provided below: Shipper continues to allow shipper direct loads without verifying the hazardous themself. Shipper passes our TAG fines to the customer when these are discovered. Will review suspending shippers ability to ship hazardous on our vessel.

column169: XPO Logistics terminal BCO experienced a UN2924 Silquest A-1101 Silane release from a 330-gallon metal tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2 ounces of product released to the metal tote body only. The plug on the top of the tote was missing which caused the release. The hole was plugged and a slosh test was completed which determined there would be no further release. The tote was wiped down, confirmed neutral, and confirmed secured for shipment on. The impacted pads and PPE were placed into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column61: Torn Off or Damaged; Torn Off or Damaged
column169: On 7/5/2024 at 3:42 AM Central Time, Canadian Pacific Kansas City Railroad (CPKC) train 242-03 derailed 29 rail cars at milepost 342.86 on the Carrington Sub near the town of Bordulac, North Dakota.  Derailed cars included six loaded tank cars transporting UN1230, Methanol, 3, PG II, RQ (Methanol), eleven loaded tank cars transporting UN1005, Ammonia, Anhydrous, 2.3(8), Toxic Inhalation Hazard, Zone D, Marine Pollutant (Ammonia, Anhydrous), RQ (Ammonia), and twelve loaded hopper cars transporting non-hazmat Polyethylene pellets. CPKC mobilized internal and railroad qualified external resources to investigate the damage and mitigate released lading. Fire was reported immediately after the derailment, with multiple cars on fire. Many of the derailed tank cars experienced heat impingement. Because of this, pressure built within tank cars caused pressure relief devices to release product into the atmosphere.  Additionally, releases occurred from holes and punctures in tank shells, and from damage incurred to manways, valves, pressure regulating devices, and other tank car appurtenances. The NTSB is investigating this incident and has requested that CPKC refrain from modifying any tank cars until it has completed its work.  Because of this, CPKC has not been able to fully assess damage which might have occurred under tank jackets. The following information is the best information available at this time.  The cars detailed below released the listed amounts in gallons from the following locations:  1) PROX 45220, loaded Methanol, Release=0.00 - minor damage to tank car did not result in a release. 2) CTCX 300362, loaded Methanol, Release=13,558.25 - heat impingement affected integrity of manway gasket (121-Gasket 308-Leaked 512-Fire, Temperature, or Heat) & pressure Relief Device (PRD) activated (144-Pressure Relief Valve or Device – Reclosing 313-Vented 512-Fire, Temperature, or Heat). 3) TILX 355610. loaded Methanol, Release=26,035.55 - tank shell was punctured on the right side between the housing and the B-End, and on the left side of the tank car directly below  the housing  (150-Tank Shell 309-Punctured 509-Derailment), liquid line valve separated from the pressure plate (134-Liquid Valve 312-Torn Off or Damaged 509-Derailment), PRD sheared off at the pressure plate (144-Pressure Relief Valve or Device – Reclosing 312-Torn Off or Damaged 509-Derailment), & 4/6 manway securement bolts were damaged. (105 Bolts or Nuts 312 Torn Off or Damaged 509 Derailment) 4) MFCX 132265, loaded Methanol, Release=26,526.48 - tank shell was punctured on the B-End & A-End (150-Tank Shell 309-Punctured 509-Derailment), the liquid valve sheared off at the flange (134-Liquid Valve 312-Torn Off or Damaged 509-Derailment), & the vapor valve & PRD sheared off at pressure plate (158 Vapor Valve 312-Torn Off or Damaged 509-Derailment) (144-Pressure Relief Valve or Device – Reclosing 312-Torn Off or Damaged 509-Derailment) 5) CTCX 300358. loaded Methanol, Release=27,849.02 -
column170: This incident is currently under investigation - no root cause has been determined.
column199: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY COMPANY

column169: On 7/5/2024 at 3:42 AM Central Time, Canadian Pacific Kansas City Railroad (CPKC) train 242-03 derailed 29 rail cars at milepost 342.86 on the Carrington Sub near the town of Bordulac, North Dakota.  Derailed cars included six loaded tank cars transporting UN1230, Methanol, 3, PG II, RQ (Methanol), eleven loaded tank cars transporting UN1005, Ammonia, Anhydrous, 2.3(8), Toxic Inhalation Hazard, Zone D, Marine Pollutant (Ammonia, Anhydrous), RQ (Ammonia), and twelve loaded hopper cars transporting non-hazmat Polyethylene pellets. CPKC mobilized internal and railroad qualified external resources to investigate the damage and mitigate released lading. Fire was reported immediately after the derailment, with multiple cars on fire. Many of the derailed tank cars experienced heat impingement. Because of this, pressure built within tank cars caused pressure relief devices to release product into the atmosphere.  Additionally, releases occurred from holes and punctures in tank shells, and from damage incurred to manways, valves, pressure regulating devices, and other tank car appurtenances. The NTSB is investigating this incident and has requested that CPKC refrain from modifying any tank cars until it has completed its work.  Because of this, CPKC has not been able to fully assess damage which might have occurred under tank jackets. The following information is the best information available at this time.  The cars detailed below released the listed amounts in gallons from the following locations:  1) PROX 45220, loaded Methanol, Release=0.00 - minor damage to tank car did not result in a release. 2) CTCX 300362, loaded Methanol, Release=13,558.25 - heat impingement affected integrity of manway gasket (121-Gasket 308-Leaked 512-Fire, Temperature, or Heat) & pressure Relief Device (PRD) activated (144-Pressure Relief Valve or Device – Reclosing 313-Vented 512-Fire, Temperature, or Heat). 3) TILX 355610. loaded Methanol, Release=26,035.55 - tank shell was punctured on the right side between the housing and the B-End, and on the left side of the tank car directly below  the housing  (150-Tank Shell 309-Punctured 509-Derailment), liquid line valve separated from the pressure plate (134-Liquid Valve 312-Torn Off or Damaged 509-Derailment), PRD sheared off at the pressure plate (144-Pressure Relief Valve or Device – Reclosing 312-Torn Off or Damaged 509-Derailment), & 4/6 manway securement bolts were damaged. column169: At 3:32 pm on Friday, July 26, 2024, During the loading process the driver failed to secure his manway before departure. The driver, after leaving Worthington Monroe, was contacted by PVS Dispatch and subsequently stopped on the side of the I-75 freeway, at the north end of the I-275 loop in Cincinnati, to tighten the bolts on the transport vehicle. Hepaco Project Manager: Bill Swope, (463) 253-5405 Bill Swope reported that the spill on the intersection of Lawton and interstate 62 amounted to approximately 3 gallons.  Hepaco, a professional environmental and emergency response company, was engaged to handle the spill. Bryan Martin, Hepaco VP, and Bill Swope, the project manager, coordinated the cleanup operations. Hepaco was dispatched to clean the spill with the supervision of the Ohio EPA, Ohio EPA: Trevor Irwin, (614) 886-2484  The prompt and coordinated response by the Worthington Monroe team, in conjunction with Hepaco and the Ohio EPA, successfully mitigated the effects of the ferrous chloride spill. Through immediate action, effective communication, and thorough cleanup efforts, the environmental and health impacts of the spill were minimized.
column170: To prevent the recurrence of hazardous materials spills and to enhance overall safety in transportation, several changes and improvements can be implemented. These include additional training and enhanced operating procedures.   Implementing these recommendations will significantly reduce the risk of hazardous materials spills and enhance the overall safety of transportation operations. By investing in training, improving packaging, enhancing operating procedures, and collaborating with industry and regulatory bodies, we can create a safer and more efficient system for transporting hazardous materials.

column169: ABF states city driver Rafael Zawadzki (00933020) called safety at 08:15PM (CDT) about a hazmat spill that was not reported earlier in the day or cleaned by CURA. ABF driver stated that a bottle of UN2789, ACETIC ACID GLACIAL, 8 (3) PG II had spilled on the floor of trailer 401322 this morning. ABF driver stated that he began to feel lightheaded, nausea, shortness of breath, and headaches throughout the day he was delivering with the trailer. ABF driver states once he arrived back to ABF113, he notified Safety about the spill and his symptoms got worse. ABF driver reported his symptoms to Rodney Cooper (Operation Supervisor) and Rodney also stated he felt those same symptoms. ABF states during the call with Mr. Cooper, he informed Safety that his 4 other workers at that time (Rafael Zawadzki, Jason Granderson, James Fortin, and Joe Keefer) had also experienced these same symptoms. ABF Safety advised that at all costs, stay away from trailer 401322 until CURA had serviced it. ABF Safety immediately notified hazmat on-call at 08:43PM about the situation and on-call stated to do a spill report like normal and call CURA out to the scene ASAP. ABF Safety called CURA at 08:57PM and CURA dispatched a team to the location arriving at 10:26PM. ABF SCM Joshua Sabolcik states that they took one employee to Ascension Saint Joseph - Elgin Hospital (847-695-3200) and his 4 other workers to Advocate Sherman Hospital (847-742-9800) in Elgin, IL for treatment.
column170: Emphasize timely reporting on behalf of the service center. ABF's policy is for all spills to be called in to the Safety Hotline immediately. Also retrain employees in proper loading procedures.

On 7/21/2024 at approximately 1100, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 261690 at the ramp facility in Anchorage, reporting a dangerous goods spill.  The shipment consisted of 8 metal cans, each individually overpacked in a fiberboard box, and then all were overpacked onto a pallet.  One the packages was reportedly damaged due to mishandling, resulting in spillage.  The damaged package was placed in a salvage drum and the entire shipment is being held, awating an amended shipper's declaration to be returned to the shipper.

The wet package was discovered during the AM sort and placed in a plastic lined hazmat tote and brought to QA for inspection. Upon inspection the package was found to be a damaged hazmat and all the proper hazmat procedures were followed. Package handler 4575314 was exposed to the leaking product and skin irritation was a result. He washed his hands with soap and water and reported the incident to his supervisor.
